  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "phil-mind-expert",
    "senderColor": "orange",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Bad idea — passage IS the argument and a philosophical experiment, not swappable",
    "content": "\n**Bad idea.**\n\nThe 道德仁义礼 passage is not an illustration of a general point -- it IS the argument. The author builds the entire reversal (top-down vs. bottom-up construction of metaphysical concepts) through the specific mechanics of how 礼 generates 仁 generates 德 generates 道 in lived experience, while the traditional framework claims the opposite direction. A Western example could illustrate the abstract point, but it would not *perform* the reversal on the reader in the same way, because the reversal depends on the reader holding the traditional sequence first and then experiencing its inversion.\n\nMore importantly, this passage is a philosophical experiment (as we discussed). The author constructs 现象礼/现象仁/现象义 as experiential handles that the reader uses to introspectively locate the bottom-up sequence. These coinages work because the reader has just seen the classical terms in the Laozi quotation. Swapping in Western terms would break the experimental apparatus.\n\nThe translation difficulty is real but it is a one-time cost: gloss the five terms once, and the reader carries them through. The passage is only a few paragraphs. The apparatus pays for itself.\n"
  }
}
